[3] Georgia

******
[1] California
Date: Thu 15 Jul 2010
Source: Google News, Agencia EFE report [in Spanish trans. Corr.SB edited]
<http://www.google.com/hostednews/epa/article/ALeqM5g8vdn-gXwY03IVU3cM34NLFVB5bQ>


An epidemic of pertussis in California has had a particularly serious
effect in Hispanic children, as the 5 children who have died from the
disease in 2010 were Latino babies, less than 3 months old.

The Department of Public Health in California (CDPH) has launched a
Spanish-language ad campaign to warn the Latino community about the
importance of vaccinating infants at 2, 4, and 6 months of age, with
a booster between 15 and 18 months of age and another between 4 and 6
years.

"Whooping cough is a highly contagious disease," warned Dr Mark
Horton, director of CDPH in a statement. "Babies who are not
vaccinated or who have not completed the series of recommended
vaccines are particularly vulnerable. The disease in this age group
often results in hospitalization and can be fatal."

For the 1st half of 2010, state health authorities reported 1337
cases of pertussis in the state, a rate 3.4 cases per 100 000
inhabitants, representing an increase of 500 percent over the same
period in 2009.

CDPH statistics show that the highest incidence of pertussis in
infants under 6 months of age occurs among Hispanics at a rate of
94.2 cases per 100 000, more than double that of African Americans.

"Studies have shown that half of children with whooping cough are
infected by their parents, particularly their mothers," states the
CDPH instructive about its prevention. "Therefore, vaccination of
parents and caregivers against whooping cough before or just after
the birth of the child is the most important way to protect babies."

