Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The state of Georgia can be seen on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00u5>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

[Cases of pertussis in previously vaccinated older children and
adults are generally attributed to waning immunity without
considering potential differences in _Bordetella pertussis_ strains.
As pointed out in 2009 by Dr Frits Mooi (see ProMED-mail Pertussis -
Australia (02): (SA) 20091108.3876): "There are now many studies
which show that outbreaks of pertussis are often associated with
changes in the _B. pertussis_ population. Most recently, we have
shown that more virulent (P3) strains have appeared which we believe
to be (partly) responsible for the outbreak in the Netherlands. The
P3 strains have emerged worldwide. Any discussion on the causes of
sudden upsurges in infectious diseases should include changes in the
pathogen population. This is even true for pertussis. (1)"

As a reminder, the 5 dose primary series for
diphtheria/tetanus/acellular pertussis (DTaP) vaccine in children is
recommended (2) at ages 2, 4, 6, 15-18 months, and 4-6 years. A
booster of Tdap (lower dose of diphtheria and pertussis immunogens)
is then recommended (2) between ages 11-12 or before age 18 if not
given. Additionally, a single dose of Tdap is now recommended in
adults (3) to be given to replace a dose of the every-10 year Td
booster for adults aged less than 65 years who have not previously
received a dose of Tdap. This dose is particularly important in
adults (pediatric health care workers, new parents, and grandparents)
who are likely to be in contact with young children of the age
precluding them from being adequately protected from pertussis. These
infants are the cohort group with the highest morbidity and mortality
from pertussis.

References
----------
1. Mooi FR, van Loo IHM, van Gent M, et al: _Bordetella pertussis_
strains with increased toxin production associated with pertussis
resurgence. Emerg Infect Dis. 2009 Aug; 15(8): 1206-13. Full paper
available at
<http://www.cdc.gov/eid/content/15/8/1206.htm>.
2. CDC: Recommended Immunization Schedules for Persons Aged 0-18
Years - United States, 2007. MMWR 2007; 55: Q1-Q4, available at
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5551a7.htm>.
3. CDC: Recommended Adult Immunization Schedule - United States,
October 2007-September 2008. MMWR 2007; 56: Q1-Q4, available at
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwR/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5641-Immunizationa1.htm>.
- Mod. LL]

[In response to the ongoing epidemic, California has expanded their
recommendations for acellular pertussis vaccines,
<http://www.cdph.ca.gov/HealthInfo/discond/Pages/Pertussis.aspx>
now recommending the use of Tdap whenever tetanus toxoid is
recommended including in those over 65, and for all women of
childbearing age. DTap is recommended for those 6 months to 6 years
of age. - Mod.LM]
